==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Conte
<hw>Conte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu>pl.
<plw>Contes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr></plu>. <ety>[F.]</ety> <def>A short
narrative or tale, esp. one dealing with surprising or marvelous
events.</def></p>

<p><q>The <qex>conte</qex> (sic) is a tale something more than a sketch,
it may be, and something less than a short story. . . . The
⟦ldquo⟧Canterbury Tales⟦rdquo⟧ are <qex>contes</qex>, most of them, if
not all, and so are some of the ⟦ldquo⟧Tales of a Wayside
Inn.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Brander Matthews.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Contection</ent>⟦br⟧
